ight complicate things.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating macro implementation options**\\\\n\\\\nI need to clarify if this applies to macros implemented with quoted expressions. It seems likely, since MacroHarness.guard is a macro, and calls in the same file may fail. I want to avoid this issue. One option could be to put the helper in a separate Scala file. The user rules say to keep tests for dynamic classes in their own files, but this library doesn't allow dynamic access classes. It might be better to call LogHelperMacro.guard directly to sidestep this problem.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering Java and Scala integration**\\\\n\\\\nI'm exploring the possibility of using Java anonymous classes in Scala if the type is inaccessible, but that doesn't seem feasible. I think keeping the test in Scala is important, while creating Java helpers could be beneficial. I need to see if using internal package dependencies from Javadoc will work. I noticed that the artifact jar has TASTy but maybe extracting it isn't an option. It seems reflection with `Class.forName` is prohibited, so I should focus on fixing run failures with minimal changes.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering macro implementation**\\\\n\\\\nI'm looking at documentation about macros, and it notes that implementations and definitions can live in the same project but not in the same source file. There's a concern about risk, suggesting it's wise to separate helpers into different files. I’m wondering if creating a new file is permitted and if it falls within the context. I could potentially create `MacroHarness.scala` in `src/test/scala`, but keeping a one-to-one mapping might make that tricky. Perhaps it's better to avoid the helper and use inline methods from the library instead.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_lHvDz7UpOqt1wJOB9yji9EzI|fc_099444905eef4ef20169fc37841b3881908ce9cd7fd